<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Astronauts Put Moon, Va., On The Map</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city that Neil Armstrong and Edwin ``Buzz''
Aldrin put on the map 20 years ago planned no official festivities
to mark the 20th anniversary of the astronauts' moon walk.
   Residents there are still trying to explain where they live.
   Before the moon walk, Moon, Va., was little more than a post
office and a bump in the road in Mathews County near the Chesapeake
Bay.
   You couldn't even find Moon on a Virginia road map.
   Today, the community of about 100 families isn't much bigger,
but at least it's on the map. The attention Moon attracted in 1969
when the Eagle landed on its celestial cousin apparently encouraged
the Virginia Department of Transportation to put it on the official
state map.
   Sometimes, even maps don't help.
   Pat Chalkley, a former Mechanicsville resident and relative
newcomer to Moon, said she sent her new address to a friend, who
replied with a note: ``Where in the hell is Moon?''
   Almost heaven, to hear Mrs. Chalkley and others describe their
community.
   ``I've heard people say that once you've seen a full moon over
the Chesapeake Bay, you never want to leave,'' said Mrs. Chalkley,
whose husband, Blanton, commutes 90 minutes to Richmond to work.
``I was sitting there the other night, looked up and saw this
absolutely gorgeous big ol' orange moon.''
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOONVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Its been 20 years since Neil Armstrong
put his historic footprint on the moon's surface, and Moonville
residents say they've waited that long for their adopted son to
visit them.
   Moonville adopted Armstrong as an honorary resident just before
he made his famous moon walk in 1969, and residents even had a
parade for him.
   But self-proclaimed Mayor Sam Peckinpaugh said the astronaut has
never been to this town, listed as Moonville on state maps and
called Moonsville by the 550 people who live here.
   If Armstrong did come, John Gunter would be the one to call.
   In 1969, Gunter, then a radio celebrity, told a joke about his
hometown that got out of hand.
   ``They're getting ready for the annual Fourth of July parade in
my hometown of Moonsville,'' he told listeners before signing off.
``It consists of a 1950 Buick with a sparkler on top!''
   More than 50 people called the station asking how to enter cars
and floats in Moonville's Fourth of July parade.
   ``I got a call saying Moonsville has to have a parade!'' Gunter
recalled.
   So the community did. And the timing was perfect.
   It was the month Armstrong was to lead the Apollo 11 mission on
the moon.
   Organizers decided to capitalize on the town's name and make
Armstrong an adopted son.
   Gunter served as grand marshal, and Neil Armstrong's brother,
Dean Armstrong, rode in the Buick with Gunter.
   Dean Armstrong told the crowd that after the moon landing, he
thought his brother, Neil, might come for a visit.
   Moonville residents are still waiting _ and hoping _ for that
visit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer's co-operative has
television talk show host Oprah Winfrey to thank for skyrocketing
sales of a cream made to soothe the chapped udders of cows.
   A recent guest on Miss Winfrey's television show touted
so-called bag balms as a beauty cure-all.
   One such balm, Bova Cream, isn't just for Bossy anymore if sales
at the Washington County Farmer's Co-op in eastern Tennessee are
any indication.
   ``We're selling like a case a week. Usually we sell about a case
a month,'' Co-op salesman Harold Hayes said.
   A 10-ounce jar of the cream sells for $2.95 at the co-op. The
cream has the same ingredients as human skin products.
   ``There's nothing wrong with it as long as they are not using it
for serious diseases,'' said Johnson City dermatologist William
Schueller.
</TEXT>
