<HEAD>100 Feet in 10 Seconds Equal How Many Slices of Bread?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The problem, as posed to 150,000 school
children on Friday, was this:
   A student, running 100 feet every 10 seconds, 24 hours a day,
requires 1,467 days to reach the moon. He or she burns 864 calories
an hour. A slice of bread contains 60 calories. How high would the
loaf of bread have to be to supply the student with enough energy
to reach the moon?
   Okay, okay. Something is left out of the problem. A sandwich
slice is about one-half inch thick. The answer is, 30,419,712
calories are represented in 506,995 slices of bread which stacked
would be 253,498 inches high, creating a loaf of bread four miles
high.
   Oh, yes. The moon averages about 240,000 miles away, though you
didn't have to know that to solve the problem.
   This problem was one of five presented on a satellite network
connecting 900 schools around the country to spark youngsters'
interest in learning and to spur appreciation science, math, and
teaching.
   It was the first of such classroom lessons sponsored by the
Challenger Center, an educational project founded by the families
of the seven astronauts who perished aboard the space shuttle
Challenger four years ago.
   ``Today, we took you on an imaginary trip to the moon,'' said
Dr. R. Lynn Bondurant Jr., chief of educational services at NASA's
Lewis Research Center who conducted the program. ``Some day you may
be on a real trip to the moon ... Remember to reach for the stars.''
   Teachers in the participating classes received matterials in
advance. The preparation showed as pupils afterward asked questions
of Michael Collins, who flew the mother ship while astronauts Neil
Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin made the walk on the moon in 1969.
   What impresses you most from that far away from home?
   ``The size of the Earth,'' said Collins. ``First you have to
find it. It is as small as your thumbnail.''
   What supplies should you take?
   ``Hydrogen,'' said Collins. Human beings need water, which is
two parts hydrogen and one part oxygen. ``You can get a lot of
oxygen out of the rocks on the moon, but you have to take hydrogen
from Earth.''
   How long will the footprints left on the moon last?
   ``I don't know,'' said Collins. Eventually, he said, they would
be obliterated by micrometeorites hitting the moon.
   Friday's lessons included calculations to find the distance to
the moon, evaluating the differences in gravity, mapping the moon,
and the Collins interview.
   In the next few weeks the student will work on designing a lunar
mining base and one plan from each school will be submitted to the
Challenger center.
   For the gravity calculations, the students were shown a clip in
which astronaut David Scott, on Apollo 15, dropped a hammer and
feather simultaneously to the moon and they hit the surface at
exactly the same time.
   What they weren't asked to calculate was one of the space age's
most enduring mysteries. How far did the golf ball that Alan
Shepard hit on the moon during the Apollo 14 mission travel in the
one-sixth gravity and no atmosphere to slow it down?
</TEXT>
