<HEAD>Former Chief Astronaut Disappointed With Space Program Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former chief astronaut says the emphasis on the
space shuttle is to blame for a slowdown in America's space program.
   Astronaut John W. Young, who flew on the first manned Gemini
mission in 1965 and later walked on the moon, expressed
disappointment with the space program's progress in a recent
interview.
   ``It is almost 20 years since we landed people on the moon,''
said Young, 57. ``And if you had asked me after the moon landing
what we'd be doing in 20 years, I'd have said we'd have a base on
the moon in 20 years.''
   Young, now a safety and engineering trouble-shooter for Johnson
Space Center's director, commanded the first and ninth shuttle
flights while serving as chief astronaut for the National
Aeronautics and Space Admininstration.
   He said the shuttles on which NASA staked its future in the
early 1970s have never been the inexpensive, quickly refurbished
workhorses that their supporters promised.
   ``I never believed it could be that way,'' Young said. ``I
wasn't involved in selling it, but I was involved in the technical
details of helping design and build it, and it was too
complicated.''
   Young said the shuttle is capable of fulfilling its creators'
expectations, but tight budgets hurt it when NASA could not afford
to stockpile spare parts for quick repairs. And, he said, the
spacecraft's design can slow repairs because some areas are hard to
reach.
   He said that quick shuttle turnarounds and reflights and routine
Florida landings never panned out, nor is the shuttle an
inexpensive way to fly.
   The basic assumption that it pays to salvage and reuse each $15
million solid-fuel rocket booster may be wrong, Young said.
   He also said the delays are affecting the supply of flight-ready
astronauts. Fourteen astronauts who flew before the Jan. 28, 1986,
Challenger explosion decided not to wait for flights to resume. The
space center has 93 astronauts and is accepting applications
through July 1 for a 1990 astronaut class.
   ``I expect there's a lot of astronauts leaving because they see
the line at the end of the tunnel,'' Young said. ``The line they've
got to stand in to get a flight is so long.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

