<HEAD>Amrstrong, Aldrin Help NASA Celebrate 20th Anniversary of Apollo
11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neil A. Armstrong and Edwin E. ``Buzz'' Aldrin
Jr. thanked NASA's rocket fuel researchers Thursday night during a
celebration marking this month's 20th anniversary of the first
manned landing on the moon.
   ``We were participants and witness to the birth of a new human
era,'' Armstrong said in brief remarks to several hundred people at
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Lewis Research
Center, which helped develop rocket fuel for the Apollo 11 flight.
   Armstrong, commander of the three-man Apollo 11 crew, and Aldrin
said present and past researchers at the center had been
instrumental in helping them accomplish the first manned lunar
landing on July 20, 1969.
   ``Their contributions were of critical importance to our
success,'' Armstrong said.
   Aldrin, who followed Armstrong out of the Eagle landing craft
onto the moon's surface, said he has expected for more than a year
that the 20th anniversary of the Apollo 11 landing would have
special meaning.
   ``I sense that the 20th anniversary is going to mean a lot for
this nation,'' said Aldrin, who said it was unfortunate that the
nation hasn't sent a manned craft to the moon since Apollo 17 in
1972.
   Aldrin called for development of a space port which would serve
as a stopover point in space using different types of transportation.
</TEXT>
